I (short bowel syndrome). Of the 11 patients with AIDS (group II) 4 developed 
catheter related infections (0.32/100 catheter days), and 1 developed a 
thrombotic occlusion. All 5 catheters were removed (3 for infection). Of the 15 
patients with lymphoma or myeloma who had 16 catheters implanted (group III), 1 
patient developed 3 infective episodes (0.05/100 catheter days), 1 catheter 
migrated and 1 occluded. All 3 catheters were removed.
CONCLUSION: Totally implantable infusion systems can safely be used for 
prolonged periods in immunocompromised patients, including those with AIDS if 
their life expectancy is reasonable.

