466. J Neuroophthalmol. 1995 Mar;15(1):36-8.

Invasive aspergillosis. A complication of treatment of temporal arteritis.

Wiggins RE Jr(1).

Author information:
(1)Asheville Eye Medical and Surgical Associates, North Carolina, USA.

Temporal arteritis is a systemic necrotizing vasculitis for which the only 
effective treatment is systemic corticosteroids. A review of the literature 
suggests that there is a significant mortality rate in untreated patients but 
that those patients who receive adequate corticosteroid treatment rarely 
experience a reduced life expectancy. I had the opportunity to evaluate a 
patient with temporal arteritis who eventually died from disseminated 
aspergillosis 6 weeks after beginning corticosteroid treatment. A high index of 
suspicion for infections with opportunistic organisms should be maintained in 
patients with temporal arteritis receiving corticosteroids.

