473. Med Decis Making. 1995 Apr-Jun;15(2):158-69. doi:
10.1177/0272989X9501500209.

Life expectancy biases in clinical decision modeling.

Kuntz KM(1), Weinstein MC.

Author information:
(1)Department of Medicine, Brigham and Women's Hospital, Boston, MA 02115, USA.

Clinical decision models often rely upon survival models predicated on 
disease-specific hazard functions combined with baseline hazard functions 
obtained from standard life tables. Two biases may arise in such a modeling 
process. First, life expectancy estimates may be biased even if estimates of 
survival probabilities are unbiased (misestimation bias). In simulation studies, 
the authors discovered that the magnitude of misestimation bias is larger as 
life expectancy increases, sample size decreases, and censoring percentage 
increases. In the context of a simple decision analysis, they found that 
